{
  "doc_id": "32937",
  "text": "We also investigated the potential role of the non-receptor tyrosine kinases, Src and JAK2. Both kinases act downstream of FGFR and their activity is also essential for TyrSTAT3 phosphorylation. Src has been described as an important kinase in STAT phosphorylation in many cell types under various conditions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , but its activity is usually dependent on upstream receptor tyrosine kinase activation [CITATION_5] . Src activation upon FGF stimulation has been previously described [CITATION_6] , and both direct and indirect interaction between Src family members and FGFR were presented [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . We show that complex formation between active FGFR1 and Src is FRS2-independent. We also show that Src potentially plays a direct role in FGF-induced STAT3 phosphorylation. On the other hand, Src can be indirectly involved in STAT3 activation by maintaining the activity and dynamics of FGFR as activation of Src and FGFR is interdependent [CITATION_9] .",
